    "Z Senator Humphrey Introduces Anti Lynching Bill WASHINGTON March 30 A NPDeclaring that the antilyn ching bill represents the heart and ctore of the Presidents Civil Rights Program Senator Hubert H Humphrey liberal Democrat from Minnesota today introduced the NAACP supported antilyncn ing bill The bill jves Federal courts jurisdiction over the crime of lynching and provides a maxi mum fine of 10000 and twenty years imprisonment for members of lynching mobs Cosponsors of the measure are Senators Robert F Wagner Democrat of New York and Wayne Morse Repub lican literal from Oregon Senator Humphrey declared that unless a man is free from the fear and threat of bodily harm and even death at the hands of a cowardly mob all of his other civ il rights are academic meaning less and will not be used The 81st Congress has a spe cial responsibility to pass the anti lynching bill Humphrey contin ued Civil rights legislation is in reality no longer a subject of deep contention and heavy debate for most Americans in most areas of the United States The platforms of both major political parties ring out in support of civil rights and human rights The President of the"
